<Base
  title="GRADUS · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="Does a language model represent epistemic modal force — the necessity in must, the possibility in might — or ride the surface modal word? A causal probe plus a graded epistemic-force dataset."
  toc={true}
>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Modal force · pilot running → resource + diagnostic paper
    </div>
    <h1>GRADUS — does a model represent modal force, or ride the word?</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      When a model reads <em>the ball must be red</em> vs. <em>might be red</em>, is it tracking the
      modal force — necessity vs. possibility — or reacting to the surface lexeme <em>must</em> / <em>might</em>?
    </p>

    <p>
      This is the one project I am actively running, and the first instance of the program: the
      structure-versus-surface question asked of <strong>modality</strong>, where it takes its
      sharpest, most falsifiable form. "Surface" = the word triggers the right behaviour
      <em>without</em> the concept; "structure" = the word is backed by an internal representation of
      force. GRADUS is the standalone precursor the Master's thesis builds on — the pilot that
      validates the instrument, plus the graded dataset that turns it into a resource.
    </p>

    <figure class="essay-fig">
      <TLFig kind="gradus" color="var(--accent-deep-purple)" />
    </figure>

    <h2>Why epistemic, and the confound it avoids</h2>
    <p>
      To read out "certainty" we need items that differ in force. Building them from
      <strong>world-structure</strong> ("only red balls" vs. "red and blue") changes the base rate of
      red, so any direction estimated from it encodes frequency, not force — and it is
      <em>alethic</em> necessity, the wrong flavor for epistemic <em>must</em>. So the pilot studies
      <strong>epistemic</strong> modality and operationalises force as evidence-based certainty:
      epistemic <em>must</em> is an evidence-licensed inference (von Fintel &amp; Gillies 2010), not
      logical necessity. The base-rate reading is kept as a competing control, not the definition.
    </p>

    <h2>The design — a causal test on a fixed model</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Define a force direction <code>D</code> with no modal word.</strong> Vary only
        evidence, hold the fact fixed: <em>all three sensors report red</em> (certain) vs. <em>one of
        three</em> (unsure). <code>D = mean(strong) − mean(weak)</code> in the residual stream at
        layer L. No modal word, so <code>D</code> cannot be a reaction to the lexeme; the fact is
        unchanged, so <code>D</code> is not base rate.</li>
      <li><strong>Sanity check.</strong> Project <em>must</em> / <em>might</em> onto <code>D</code>;
        expect <em>must</em> at the certain end. Near-guaranteed — a check, not evidence.</li>
      <li><strong>The test.</strong> Ablate <code>D</code> (projection: <code>h ← h − (h·D̂)D̂</code>)
        while the model answers the certainty question on a <em>might</em> item. If certainty jumps
        toward the <em>must</em> level, handling <em>might</em> <strong>needed</strong> the force
        concept — structure. If nothing moves — surface.</li>
      <li><strong>Competing control <code>D′</code>.</strong> Build the base-rate direction the naive
        way and ablate it from the same items. Ablating <code>D</code> breaks <em>might</em> but
        ablating <code>D′</code> does not → the model uses modal force, not base-rate frequency.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Pilot — first run (a smoke test, not yet a finding)</h2>
    <p>
      Qwen2.5-0.5B-Instruct, one evidence family, best layer L* = 9. The plumbing reads correctly and
      the predicted signature appears:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Readout valid: strong evidence 0.391 &gt; weak 0.174 — certainty tracks evidence.</li>
      <li>Ablating <strong>D</strong> raises <em>might</em>'s certainty 0.307 → 0.459 (<strong>+0.152</strong>);
        ablating the base-rate control <strong>D′</strong> does not (−0.033). The structure signature,
        with the confound behaving correctly.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">
      Honest caveats that keep this a smoke test: ablating D <em>overshoots</em> (might ends above the
      must level); the must–might baseline gap is small (0.063); and there is no random-direction
      control yet, so generic disruption is not yet excluded. Next: norm-matched random-direction
      controls, scale to 1.5B, and 2–3 more evidence families for convergence.
    </p>

    <h2>GRADUS — the graded dataset that makes it a paper</h2>
    <p>
      The binary probe becomes a <strong>resource + a graded diagnostic</strong> with GRADUS: a
      constructed, lightly-normed dataset placing modal / certainty expressions on a graded
      <strong>epistemic-force</strong> scale in matched frames —
      <code>might/could &lt; may/possibly &lt; probably &lt; should &lt; must &lt; certainly</code> —
      each item carrying a force target <code>t ∈ [0,1]</code>. It is the modal analog of Cho's GraSD
      (constructed and graded), not IWCS-style sense annotation on natural data (entangled, and the
      reason a read-only probe there yields uninterpretable negatives).
    </p>
    <p>
      The payoff is a <strong>calibration test</strong>: is the model's internal certainty axis
      continuous and monotone in <code>t</code> (Lassiter-style degree semantics), or clustered with a
      gap between possibility and necessity (categorical / threshold)? This turns the pilot's scope
      caveat — force vs. graded confidence — into an empirical question, and the dataset itself is a
      citable resource, and the natural artifact to hand the developmental collaboration.
    </p>

    <h2>Relation to the thesis</h2>
    <p>
      GRADUS validates the instrument on a <em>fixed</em> model. The Master's thesis turns the same
      instrument on the <em>learning process</em>: does modal force <strong>emerge during training</strong>
      as the linguistic input shifts — can a learner built from language alone develop it, and what in
      the input drives it (read across Pythia checkpoints, then controlled retraining)? The thesis
      gets no card here until it has results; GRADUS is the running precursor it reuses.
    </p>

    <h2>Scope &amp; claim discipline</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Epistemic only</strong> (must / might as evidence-based inference). Deontic and
        circumstantial are out of scope.</li>
      <li>Behavioural / representational claim only: <em>the model's handling of the modal word is (not)
        load-bearing on an evidence-based force representation</em> — never "the model understands
        modality".</li>
      <li>No claim about training-time induction (that is the thesis) and nothing about humans:
        convergence ≠ homology.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Status</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Pilot run (Qwen2.5-0.5B): plumbing valid, structure signature present, honest smoke-test caveats above.</li>
      <li>Next: random-direction control, scale-up, multi-family convergence; then GRADUS norming and the calibration test.</li>
      <li>Deliverable: a released, documented graded epistemic-force dataset paired with its diagnostic use — a resource + diagnostic paper.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
</Base>
